{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "chinese-phil-expert",
    "senderColor": "cyan",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "YES to critical Afterword — correct placement for scholarly context",
    "content": "**YES** -- include a critical Afterword.\n\nThis is the structurally correct placement for everything we decided against putting before the essays. After the reader has undergone the experiential sequences, a critical afterword can do what we all agreed the work itself does not need done beforehand: position the reversal argument within the Chinese commentarial tradition (Heshang Gong, Wang Bi, Xunzi's 礼论), draw out the Neo-Confucian connections the author leaves implicit (Zhu Xi's 理/气, Wang Yangming's 良知), note the Yogacara resonances with 境, and situate the poetic stance relative to Western post-nihilist responses. The reader will have already formed their own experience of the text; the Afterword then enriches that experience with scholarly context rather than pre-shaping it. This is exactly how classical Chinese philosophical texts have traditionally been accompanied -- the commentary (注/疏) comes after the text, not before."
  }
}
